.TH units 1
.SH NAME
\*Lunits\*O \- Converts units from one measure to another
.SH SYNOPSIS
.PP
.sS
\*Lunits\*O
\*O[\*L\(hy\*O]
\*O[\*Vfile\*O]
.sE
.SH DESCRIPTION
.iX "units command"
.iX "converting measures"
.PP
The \*Lunits\*O command converts quantities expressed in one
measurement to their equivalents in another.  The \*Lunits\*O command is an
interactive command.  It prompts you for the unit you want to
convert from and the unit you want to convert to.  The \*Lunits\*O command
does multiplicative scale changes only.  That is, \*Lunits\*O can convert
from one value to another only when the conversion is done with a
multiplication factor.  For example, \*Lunits\*O cannot convert between
degrees Fahrenheit and degrees Celsius because the value of 32
must be added or subtracted in the conversion.
.PP
You can specify a quantity as a multiplicative combination of units,
optionally preceded by a numeric multiplier.
.PP
Indicate powers by entering suffixed positive integers and indicate
division with a \*L/\*O (slash).
.PP
The \*Lunits\*O command recognizes \*Llb\*O as a unit of mass, but considers
\*Lpound\*O to be the British pound sterling.   Compound names
are run together (for example, \*Llightyear\*O).  Prefix British
units differing from their American counterparts with \*Lbr\*O
