.SH EXAMPLES
.PP
To start the \*Lunits\*O command, enter:
.iS
units
.iE
Now you can try the following examples.
.AL
.LI
To display conversion factors, enter:
.iS
\*Cyou have:\*O \*Lin\*O
\*Cyou want:\*O \*Lcm\*O
.iE
.oS
* 2.540000e+00
/ 3.937008e-01
.oE
.IP
The output from the \*Lunits\*O command tells you to multiply the
number of inches by 2.540000e+00 to get centimeters, and to multiply
the number of centimeters by 3.937008e-01 to get inches.
.IP
These numbers are in standard exponential notation, so
3.937008e-01 means 3.937008 x 10-1, which is
the same as 0.3937008.  The second number is always the reciprocal
of the first; for example, 2.54 equals 1/0.3937008.
.LI
To convert a measurement to different units, enter:
.iS
\*Cyou have:\*O \*L5 years\*O
\*Cyou want:\*O \*Lmicrosec\*O
.iE
.oS
* 1.577846e+14
/ 6.337753e-15
.oE
.IP
The output shows that 5 years equals 1.577846 x 1014 microseconds,
and that 1 microsecond equals 6.337753 x 10-15 years.
.LI
To give fractions in measurements, enter:
.iS
\*Cyou have:\*O \*L1|3 mi\*O
\*Cyou want:\*O \*Lkm\*O
.iE
.oS
* 5.364480e-01
/ 1.864114e+00
.oE
.IP
The \*L|\*O (vertical bar) indicates division, so 1|3 means one-third.
This shows that one-third mile is the same as 0.536448 kilometers.
.LI
To include exponents in measurements, enter:
.iS
\*Cyou have:\*O \*L1.2-5 gal\*O
\*Cyou want:\*O \*Lfloz\*O
.iE
.oS
* 1.536000e-03
/ 6.510417e+02
.oE
.IP
The expression 1.2-5 gal is the equivalent of 1.2 x 10-5.  Do not
type an e before the exponent.  This example shows that 1.2 x 10-5
(0.000012) gallons equal 1.536 x 10-3 (0.001536) fluid ounces.
.LI
To specify complex units, enter:
.iS
\*Cyou have:\*O \*Lgram centimeter/second2\*O
\*Cyou want:\*O \*Lkg-m/sec2\*O
.iE
.oS
* 1.000000e-05
/ 1.000000e+05
.oE
.IP
The units gram centimeter/second2 mean
"grams x centimeters/second2." Similarly, kg-m/sec2 means
"kilograms x meters/sec2," which is often read as "kilogram-meters per
seconds squared".
.LI
If the units you specify after you have
and you want are incompatible, enter:
.iS
\*Cyou have:\*O \*Lft\*O
\*Cyou want:\*O \*Llb\*O
.iE
.oS
conformability
3.048000e-01 m
4.535924e-01 kg
.oE
.IP
The message \*Cconformability\*O means the units you specified cannot
be converted.  Feet measure length, and pounds measure mass, so
converting from one to the other does not make sense.  Therefore,
the \*Lunits\*O command displays the equivalent of each value in
standard units.
.IP
In other words, this example shows that 1 foot equals 0.3048
meters and that 1 pound equals 0.4535924 kilograms. The \*Lunits\*O
command shows the equivalents in meters and kilograms because the
command considers these units to be standard measures of length
and mass.
.IP
Entering \*L<Ctrl-d>\*O causes you to exit from the \*Lunits\*O program.
.LE
